Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective¶

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired the firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist at EasyVisa have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

### function to plot distributions wrt target


def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
In [25]:
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

Comment:¶

  • The F1-score is chosen as the primary metric to evaluate model performance. This is a deliberate choice to balance two competing business needs in the OFLC visa certification process:

  • High Recall (Sensitivity): To minimize the number of qualified visa applicants wrongly rejected (false negatives). These cases can result in missed opportunities for U.S. employers seeking talent abroad.

  • Strong Precision: To limit the number of unqualified applications incorrectly certified (false positives), which could lead to non-compliance with U.S. labor protection laws.

  • Using Recall alone may result in many false approvals.

  • Accuracy is misleading in imbalanced datasets (66.8% Certified vs. 33.2% Denied).

  • F1-score is the most balanced metric for this classification task.

  • It also defines a parameter grid for tuning:
  • n_estimators: Number of trees, max_depth: Tree depth, min_samples_split: Minimum samples required to split a node

Metrics and Confusion Matrix Functions¶

First, let's create functions to calculate different metrics and confusion matrix so that we don't have to use the same code repeatedly for each model.

  • The model_performance_classification_sklearn function will be used to check the model performance of models.
  • The confusion_matrix_sklearn function will be used to plot the confusion matrix.
In [42]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn


def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, X, y_true):
    """
    Compute accuracy, recall, precision, and F1 for a fitted sklearn classifier.
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(X)
    acc = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)
    rec = recall_score(y_true, y_pred)
    prec = precision_score(y_true, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_pred)
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": [acc], "Recall": [rec], "Precision": [prec], "F1": [f1]}
    )
    return df_perf
In [43]:
# Defining a function to generate confusion matrix metrics to evaluate the performance of classification model built using scikit-learn
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, X, y_true):
    """
    Plot confusion matrix with raw counts and percentages.
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(X)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            [
                f"{item}\n{item / cm.flatten().sum():.2%}"
                for item in cm.flatten()
            ]
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="", cmap="Blues")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
    plt.show()

Comment:¶

  • GridSearchCV was used to tune Random Forest on the oversampled training set using F1-score (Certified-focused) as the evaluation metric. After evaluating 60 combinations, the best parameters were found to be: max_depth=10, min_samples_split=2, n_estimators=200, optimizing the model's ability to detect certified visa cases effectively.

  • The choice of F1‐score (instead of pure Recall) as my primary scorer was a deliberate choice to balance two competing needs:

    1. Recall alone can drive up false positives. In our business context, missing a true “Certified” application (a false negative) is very costly, but we also don’t want to waste too much time chasing low‐probability positives. A pure‐Recall focus would tolerate an unbounded number of false positives in order to drive recall up.

    2. F1‐score strikes a middle ground between Recall and Precision.

Comment:¶

1. BaggingClassifier_Orig¶

  • Bagging achieved an F1 score of 0.768 (validation) and 0.771 (test), with recall around 76% and precision near 77% across both sets. It offers consistent but moderate performance, making it a safe but less aggressive model for OFLC’s visa shortlisting.

  • Confusion Matrix Insight:

  • Correctly classified a majority of Certified applications, but moderate number of Denied cases were incorrectly labeled as Certified.
  • True Positives (TP): High, but not the best among models.
  • False Negatives (FN): Still present → Some eligible applicants were missed.
  • Business Impact:
  • In the context of OFLC’s goal to streamline visa certification, Bagging provides balanced but conservative performance. It may not be ideal where maximizing approved candidates is critical, but can serve as a safe baseline model where both certification and denial are equally sensitive decisions.

2. RandomForestClassifier_Orig¶

  • Random Forest delivered an F1 score of 0.797 (validation) and 0.817 (test), with recall improving from 82.9% to 86.1%, and precision steady at ~77.7%. This model balances accuracy and robustness, making it highly effective for confidently shortlisting qualified foreign applicants.

  • Confusion Matrix Insight:

  • Excellent balance: High TP with low FP and FN.
  • Certified cases are accurately captured, and Denied cases are less likely to be incorrectly passed.
  • High generalization: Strong validation and test consistency.
  • Business Impact:
  • For OFLC, Random Forest is a high-confidence model for shortlisting credible applicants without compromising compliance. It reduces missed approvals and avoids overwhelming the system with false certifications—a critical feature given the volume (775K+ cases/year).

3. GradientBoostingClassifier_Orig (GBM)¶

  • GBM achieved the highest overall performance, with F1 scores of 0.820 (validation) and 0.833 (test), recall up to 88.9%, and precision over 78%. It is the best candidate for OFLC when minimizing missed certifications is critical.

  • Confusion Matrix Insight:

  • Strong TP rate, slightly higher FP compared to RF.
  • Best at identifying Certified applicants but may pass a few Denied ones.
  • Delivers high coverage of eligible cases.
  • Business Impact:
  • Perfect for OFLC’s mission of identifying qualified foreign workers quickly. With the highest F1, GBM ensures maximum approvals with minimal oversight, aligning with the push for automation amid rising application volumes. It's ideal when recall is more valuable than occasional false positives.

4. AdaBoostClassifier_Orig bold text¶

  • AdaBoost had the highest recall, reaching 90.0% on the test set, with F1 scores of 0.816 (validation) and 0.828 (test). Precision hovered around 76.6%, making it ideal for OFLC workflows focused on ensuring strong applicants are not overlooked, even if some denials are misclassified.

  • Confusion Matrix Insight:

  • Lowest false negatives — very few Certified applications are missed.
  • Slightly higher false positives — some Denied cases may be classified as Certified.
  • Prioritizes not missing strong applicants, even if it flags a few marginal ones.
  • Business Impact:
  • In OFLC’s context, AdaBoost is highly suited for candidate shortlisting tools, where missing a qualified applicant is more costly than extra review of Denied ones. It supports frontline automation and can drastically reduce manual review load by surfacing strong candidates confidently.

5. XGBoostClassifier_Orig¶

  • XGBoost produced F1 scores of 0.807 (validation) and 0.812 (test), with recall around 87.4% and precision at 77.2%. It performs closely to AdaBoost but with slightly better balance, offering scalability and resilience in high-volume visa screening.

  • Confusion Matrix Insight:

  • Very similar behavior to AdaBoost: high TP, moderate FP.
  • Slightly more balanced than AdaBoost in some cases.
  • Strong recall without overfitting.
  • Business Impact:
  • Best when OFLC wants robustness, scalability, and recall in a production-ready solution. XGBoost excels under class imbalance and can scale to millions of records, ideal for nationwide visa application processing with batch predictions or real-time evaluation.

6. DecisionTreeClassifier_Orig¶

  • Decision Tree performed the lowest, with F1 scores of 0.748 (validation) and 0.745 (test), recall up to 75.5%, and lower precision around 73.5%. While not suited for production predictions, it remains useful for transparent policy modeling and explainability.

  • Confusion Matrix Insight:

  • More false negatives and more false positives compared to others.
  • Likely to overfit on training data and underperform on unseen data.
  • Simpler model, weaker generalization.
  • Business Impact:
  • Decision Tree may serve as a baseline or explanatory model but is not recommended for operational use by OFLC. It can be useful in communicating rules or building interpretable dashboards, but not for production-level predictions.

  • Business Impact:

  • Slightly higher False Positives than RF, but acceptable considering the recall advantage.
  • Excellent at covering a wide set of eligible profiles.
  • Business Impact:
  • With the highest F1 and recall among SMOTE models, GBM_SMOTE is the top choice for OFLC when the priority is high approval coverage with minimal omission of worthy candidates. It supports proactive workforce planning and minimizes talent loss.

4. AdaBoostClassifier_SMOTE¶

  • Slight increase in False Positives compared to GBM, but not extreme.
  • Great for catching edge cases that may have been overlooked before.

  • Business Impact:

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Best practices for hyperparameter tuning in AdaBoost:

n_estimators:

  • Start with a specific number (50 is used in general) and increase in steps: 50, 75, 85, 100

  • Use fewer estimators (e.g., 50 to 100) if using complex base learners (like deeper decision trees)

  • Use more estimators (e.g., 100 to 150) when learning rate is low (e.g., 0.1 or lower)

  • Avoid very high values unless performance keeps improving on validation

learning_rate:

  • Common values to try: 1.0, 0.5, 0.1, 0.01

  • Use 1.0 for faster training, suitable for fewer estimators

  • Use 0.1 or 0.01 when using more estimators to improve generalization

  • Avoid very small values (< 0.01) unless you plan to use many estimators (e.g., >500) and have sufficient data

Best practices for hyperparameter tuning in Random Forest:

n_estimators:

  • Start with a specific number (50 is used in general) and increase in steps: 50, 75, 100, 125
  • Higher values generally improve performance but increase training time
  • Use 100-150 for large datasets or when variance is high

min_samples_leaf:

  • Try values like: 1, 2, 4, 5, 10
  • Higher values reduce model complexity and help prevent overfitting
  • Use 1–2 for low-bias models, higher (like 5 or 10) for more regularized models
  • Works well in noisy datasets to smooth predictions

max_features:

  • Try values: "sqrt" (default for classification), "log2", None, or float values (e.g., 0.3, 0.5)
  • "sqrt" balances between diversity and performance for classification tasks
  • Lower values (e.g., 0.3) increase tree diversity, reducing overfitting
  • Higher values (closer to 1.0) may capture more interactions but risk overfitting

max_samples (for bootstrap sampling):

  • Try float values between 0.5 to 1.0 or fixed integers
  • Use 0.6–0.9 to introduce randomness and reduce overfitting
  • Smaller values increase diversity between trees, improving generalization

Best practices for hyperparameter tuning in Gradient Boosting:

n_estimators:

  • Start with 100 (default) and increase: 100, 200, 300, 500
  • Typically, higher values lead to better performance, but they also increase training time
  • Use 200–500 for larger datasets or complex problems
  • Monitor validation performance to avoid overfitting, as too many estimators can degrade generalization

learning_rate:

  • Common values to try: 0.1, 0.05, 0.01, 0.005
  • Use lower values (e.g., 0.01 or 0.005) if you are using many estimators (e.g., > 200)
  • Higher learning rates (e.g., 0.1) can be used with fewer estimators for faster convergence
  • Always balance the learning rate with n_estimators to prevent overfitting or underfitting

subsample:

  • Common values: 0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 1.0
  • Use a value between 0.7 and 0.9 for improved generalization by introducing randomness
  • 1.0 uses the full dataset for each boosting round, potentially leading to overfitting
  • Reducing subsample can help reduce overfitting, especially in smaller datasets

max_features:

  • Common values: "sqrt", "log2", or float (e.g., 0.3, 0.5)
  • "sqrt" (default) works well for classification tasks
  • Lower values (e.g., 0.3) help reduce overfitting by limiting the number of features considered at each split

Best practices for hyperparameter tuning in XGBoost:

n_estimators:

  • Start with 50 and increase in steps: 50,75,100,125.
  • Use more estimators (e.g., 150-250) when using lower learning rates
  • Monitor validation performance
  • High values improve learning but increase training time

subsample:

  • Common values: 0.5, 0.7, 0.8, 1.0
  • Use 0.7–0.9 to introduce randomness and reduce overfitting
  • 1.0 uses the full dataset in each boosting round; may overfit on small datasets
  • Values < 0.5 are rarely useful unless dataset is very large

gamma:

  • Try values: 0 (default), 1, 3, 5, 8
  • Controls minimum loss reduction needed for a split
  • Higher values make the algorithm more conservative (i.e., fewer splits)
  • Use values > 0 to regularize and reduce overfitting, especially on noisy data

colsample_bytree:

  • Try values: 0.3, 0.5, 0.7, 1.0
  • Fraction of features sampled per tree
  • Lower values (e.g., 0.3 or 0.5) increase randomness and improve generalization
  • Use 1.0 when you want all features considered for every tree

colsample_bylevel:

  • Try values: 0.3, 0.5, 0.7, 1.0
  • Fraction of features sampled at each tree level (i.e., per split depth)
  • Lower values help in regularization and reducing overfitting
  • Often used in combination with colsample_bytree for fine control over feature sampling

param_dist_ada = {
    "n_estimators": [50, 75, 100, 125],
    "learning_rate": [1.0, 0.5, 0.1, 0.01],
}
ada = AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=1)

# Define the F1 scorer
f1_scorer = make_scorer(f1_score, pos_label=1)

# Run RandomizedSearchCV (single‐process to avoid pickling issues)
rs_ada = RandomizedSearchCV(
    estimator=ada,
    param_distributions=param_dist_ada,
    scoring=f1_scorer,
    n_iter=8,
    cv=StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=1),
    random_state=1,
    n_jobs=1,
    verbose=2,
)

# Fit on SMOTE‐oversampled training data (X_train_sm, y_train_sm)

AdaBoostClassifier_Tuned_SMOTE Results¶

  • After hyperparameter tuning, AdaBoost with SMOTE achieved a cross-validated F1 score of 0.8031, with the best combination being n_estimators=75 and learning_rate=1.0. This refined configuration enhances both recall and precision beyond the default settings, making the model more aggressive in identifying qualified applicants.

  • Confusion Matrix Insight:

  • On the Validation Set, the model correctly identified 3,923 Certified applicants, representing 57.0% of all cases. However, it missed 671 eligible applications (Certified cases wrongly denied), which accounts for 9.75% of the total. At the same time, it incorrectly approved 1,175 Denied applications (false positives), about 17.1%, while correctly rejecting 1,110 Denied cases, approximately 16.1%.

  • On the Test Set, the tuned model correctly classified 445 Certified applicants, which is 58.2% of the test data. It only missed 66 Certified applicants (false negatives), a low 8.6% error rate. For Denied applications, it made 128 errors by misclassifying them as Certified (16.7%) and correctly rejected 126, which is 16.5%.

  • Across both sets, the model maintains a high TP rate with consistently low FN, showing that Certified applicants are rarely missed. However, it trades this off with a moderate rise in FP, indicating a few Denied applicants may slip through.

  • Business Impact:

  • For the OFLC, AdaBoost_Tuned_SMOTE offers an optimized model that excels in high recall, making it well-suited for early-stage applicant shortlisting. With a fine-tuned learning rate and estimator count, it minimizes the risk of rejecting deserving foreign workers, which is critical given workforce shortages.

  • Its balanced performance and high generalization also suggest it can be safely scaled to national screening pipelines, especially in automation-driven review queues where the cost of false negatives is more critical than the cost of false positives.

  • This model is ideal for settings where ensuring no qualified applicant is missed outweighs the overhead of a few manual rechecks.

  • Prevailing wage contributes roughly 13%, confirming that higher compensation levels improve approval odds, which directly supports OFLC’s focus on fair labor practices and wage protection.

  • Advanced academic qualifications — Master’s and Doctorate degrees — together contribute around 17%, reinforcing that higher education continues to play a central role in driving favorable visa outcomes.

    Other notable drivers include continent of origin (Europe), unit of wage (Yearly), region of U.S. employment (Midwest and South), and number of employees, each contributing between 2% and 6%, and while individually less dominant, they still play a meaningful role in shaping model decisions.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

  • 1. Automate Shortlisting with Gradient Boosting (GBM_Orig)

    Insight: GBM_Orig achieved one of the highest F1 scores (0.8196), with Recall of 87.5% and Precision of 77.1%, outperforming many tuned or resampled models.

    Recommendation: Deploy GBM_Orig as the primary shortlisting model. Its strong balance of recall and precision minimizes missed approvals while limiting false certifications.

  • 2. Flag Low-Education Applicants for Manual Review

    Insight: 'High School' education was the single most influential feature, contributing just under 28% of model decisions — indicating a high negative weight.

    Recommendation: Add a flag or lower-risk score for applicants with only high school education. Direct these for manual review or secondary justification during certification.

  • 3. Prioritize Experienced Candidates

    Insight: Candidates with job experience are significantly more likely to be certified, contributing over 15% to model decisions.

    Recommendation: Add automatic bonus points or weighting in the application scoring for candidates with proven work history, especially if the experience aligns with U.S. labor shortages.

  • 4. Use Prevailing Wage as a Gatekeeper Variable

    Insight: Higher prevailing wages correlate with higher certification odds, contributing about 13% to decision-making.

    Recommendation: Consider enforcing a minimum prevailing wage threshold by job type and region to pre-filter applications that are unlikely to be approved.

  • 5. Target Skilled Regions for Employer Campaigns

    Insight: While geography (e.g., Europe) contributes to predictions, it is likely a proxy for other variables (education, wage, etc.).

    Recommendation: Use regional trends to guide targeted outreach to employers with historically high success rates, but avoid region-based applicant screening directly to stay compliant with anti-bias principles.

  • 6. Focus Resource Allocation on Full-Time, Yearly-Wage Applications

    Insight: Applications marked as full-time and offering yearly wages were more likely to be approved than hourly/monthly roles.

    Recommendation: Direct OFLC reviewers to prioritize full-time, annual-salaried roles, which show higher certification rates and lower risk of labor market disruption.

  • 7. Avoid Oversampling for Production; Prefer Natural Distributions

    Insight: Despite SMOTE and undersampling aiding balance during training, original full data models (like GBM_Orig) often outperformed tuned/oversampled ones.

    Recommendation: For deployment, use naturally distributed, high-volume data and avoid synthetic resampling unless the imbalance becomes extreme or recall drops significantly.

  • 8. Maintain DecisionTree_Tuned_Orig for Explainability

    Insight: This model achieved 92% recall, with clear rule-based paths, making it great for justifications and internal audits.

    Recommendation: Use DecisionTree_Tuned_Orig in dashboards or compliance reviews to help explain why applicants were denied or certified.

  • 9. Regularly Monitor False Positives

    Insight: Models like AdaBoost and XGBoost showed high recall but also more false positives, meaning some unqualified applicants were marked “Certified.”

    Recommendation: Establish a post-prediction review layer for high-risk roles (e.g., where wages are close to the minimum) to catch false approvals before final certification.

  • 10. Establish a Periodic Re-tuning Process

    Insight: Though tuning sometimes didn’t outperform GBM_Orig, changes in application volume and applicant demographics will shift over time.

    Recommendation: Re-evaluate model performance quarterly, especially as policy changes or demand shifts. Introduce hyperparameter tuning pipelines for continuous optimization.

  • 11. Build a Recommendation Engine for Applicants

    Insight: Many rejected applicants lacked just one or two key features (e.g., higher wage or experience).

    Recommendation: Provide personalized feedback or a recommendation tool that tells applicants how to improve their chances—e.g., “Gain 2 years of experience,” or “Target $X wage.”

  • 12. Visual Dashboards for OFLC Analysts

    Insight: Model insights (e.g., feature importance, rejection trends) can empower policy decisions.

    Recommendation: Integrate a dashboard interface showing live trends in top rejection factors, region-wise success rates, and model confidence to support data-informed certification policies.
